def loadSound(mainSound, sampleRate=22050):
    global mainArray
    global sr   # sample rate
    mainArray, sr = librosa.load(mainSound, sr=sampleRate)

In [7]:
def bandpassFilter(freqMin, freqMax):
    """
    inspired from: https://github.com/alessandro-gentilini/opencv_exercises-butterworth/issues/1
    """
    tempFft = ftSound.copy()
    
    frequencies = np.fft.fftfreq(mainArray.shape[0], d=1.0/sr)
    
    # Indizes des unteren endes finden
    boundLow = (np.abs(frequencies - freqMin)).argmin()
    # indizes des oberen endes finden
    boundHigh = (np.abs(frequencies - freqMax)).argmin()

    tempFft[:boundLow] = 0
    tempFft[-boundLow:] = 0
    tempFft[boundHigh:-boundHigh] = 0
    
    transformIfft(tempFft)

Introduction¶

A frequency describes the cycles per second for any signal. Frequencies are given in Hertz.

$$ \begin{aligned} Hz = 1s^{-1} \end{aligned} $$

The human ear can still grasp the spectrum from 20Hz - 20,000Hz. However, human speech can only stretch from 85Hz - 100Hz.

The following briefly describes the two main characteristics of tones.

1) Frequencies: the higher the frequency, the higher the tone. Thus, lower tones are achieved with lower frequencies.

2) Amplitude: the higher the amplitude of a sound, the louder it is. Conversely, the smaller the amplitude, the quieter the sound.

As you can possibly hear from this tone, this is a signal that is composed of several signals with different frequencies.

This is based on the principle of interference. The deflection of the individual signals is added together, which increases or decreases the amplitude in the combined signal. Due to the different amplitude sizes, you get the sound that gets louder and quieter.

Execution of the Fourier transform¶

With the help of the Fourier transformation, a periodic time-discrete signal can be transferred from the time spectrum to the frequency spectrum.

This method is often used in signal processing to identify the individual frequencies in a composite signal or to represent non-periodic functions through the linear combination of sine and cosine functions (which have different frequencies).

Since in practice there is usually a large number of discrete values, a discrete Fourier transformation is carried out. Different variations of the Fourier transformation are possible, which are noticeable in the sign of the exponent or the normalization. This variant of the Fourier transformation is used in the following.

$$ \begin{aligned} X[k] = \sum_{n=0}^{N-1} x[n]*e^{-2\pi i \dfrac{mk}{N}} \quad \quad \quad k = 0, .., n-1 \end{aligned} $$

Execution of the inverse Fourier transform¶

With the inverse Fourier transformation, the reverse transformation from the frequency spectrum into the time spectrum is fulfilled.

In this implementation, normalization is done here. (shown with $\dfrac{1}{N}$).

$$ \begin{aligned} x[n] = \dfrac{1}{N} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1} X[k]*e^{2\pi i \dfrac{mk}{N}} \quad \quad \quad m = 0, .., n-1 \end{aligned} $$
In [15]:
def transformIfft(fftData):
    global iftSound
    iftSound = np.fft.ifft(fftData)
    print("    RMSE :" + str(calcRMSE()))
    slider = interact(drawIftPlot, zoomFaktor=widgets.IntSlider(min=0, max=44100, step= 10, value=22050, continuous_update=False))
    display(slider)

Degree of deviation¶

The Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) is used to determine the deviation from the original to the inverse Fourier-transformed signal. $$ \begin{aligned} RMSE = \sqrt{\dfrac{1}{N} \sum_{i=0}^{N}(y_i - \hat{y_i})^2} \\ \\ N = Number \space of\space compared\space values\\ y_i = Actual\space data\\ \hat{y_i} = Calculated \space data (Predicted\space data\space often)\\ \end{aligned} $$

With the aid of this method, an assessment can be made about the agreement between a generated signal and an existing signal. Common use of the RMSE is when predicting data. Here, predicted data (corona data, weather data, etc.) are compared with actual (occurred) data in order to assess the accuracy of an algorithm.

The larger the RMSE, the further away the compared values are and thus the algorithm used is worse. The smaller the RMSE, the better the algorithm becomes. A value of 0 would be ideal, but in reality it is almost never reached.

In [16]:
def calcRMSE():
    RMSE = sqrt(np.square(np.subtract(iftSound.real, mainArray)).mean())
    return RMSE.real

Filtering the signal¶

With the help of a bandpass, a frequency range is selected that is transformed back into the time spectrum with the help of the Fourier transformation.

The inverse transformation only takes into account frequencies that are in the specified frequency band (between freqMin and freqMax). Frequencies that are not in the specified frequency band are not taken into account, which can result in deviations from the original signal.

It should be noted that the limits are not included in the interactive plot below. This means that if the signal has a frequency of 410 Hz and freqMin is set to 410 Hz, this frequency is not taken into account and thus the RMSE increases. With a freqMin of 400 Hz and a frqMax> than 410 Hz, the frequency would be in the band pass. If this is the only frequency in the signal, the RMSE would be very small.
